Biography of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang

Zhang Shizhi, the Tingwei, was from Duyang. His courtesy name was Ji. He had an elder brother named Zhong, with whom he lived. He became a Qilang through his family wealth and served Emperor Xiaowen. For ten years he received no promotion and remained unknown. Shizhi said, "Serving long in office has diminished Zhong's estate; this will not succeed." He wished to resign and return home. The Zhonglangjiang Yuan Ang knew his worth, regretted his departure, and thus requested to transfer Shizhi to fill the post of Yezhe. After Shizhi had finished his audience, he spoke beforehand about matters of advantage. Emperor Wen said, "Keep it low; do not make high-flown arguments. Let it be something that can be implemented now." Thus Shizhi spoke at length about affairs between Qin and Han, about why Qin lost and why Han rose. Emperor Wen praised him and appointed Shizhi as Yezhe Pushi.

Shizhi accompanied the emperor on a journey and ascended the Tiger Enclosure. The emperor asked the Shanglin Wei for the register of all birds and beasts. After more than ten questions, the Wei looked left and right, unable to answer anything. The Sifu of the Tiger Enclosure, standing aside, answered the emperor's questions about the register of birds and beasts in great detail, wishing to display his ability to respond orally without end. Emperor Wen said, "Should officials not be like this? The Wei is worthless!" He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the Sifu as the Ling of Shanglin. Shizhi had previously stepped forward and said, "Your Majesty, what kind of man is the Marquis of Jiang, Zhou Bo?" The emperor said, "He is a worthy elder." He asked again, "What kind of man is Zhang Xiangruo, the Marquis of Dongyang?" The emperor again said, "He is a worthy elder." Shizhi said, "The Marquis of Jiang and the Marquis of Dongyang are called worthy elders, yet these two, when speaking of affairs, could not even get words out of their mouths. How could they imitate this Sifu, who is garrulous, sharp-tongued, and quick-witted! Moreover, Qin entrusted its affairs to clerks skilled in writing and law; officials competed to excel in haste and harsh scrutiny. Yet their defect was merely formalism, without any reality of compassion. Therefore they did not hear of their faults, declined gradually until the Second Generation, and the empire collapsed like earth. Now, Your Majesty, because the Sifu is eloquent, you intend to promote him beyond his rank. I fear the world will follow the wind and bow down, competing in eloquence without substance. Moreover, the transformation of the lower by the upper is faster than shadow and echo; one cannot be too careful in appointments and actions." Emperor Wen said, "Good." He then stopped and did not appoint the Sifu.

The emperor mounted his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride beside him, proceeded slowly, and asked Shizhi about the defects of Qin. Shizhi answered fully and truthfully. Upon reaching the palace, the emperor appointed Shizhi as the Ling of the Gongche.

Soon after, the Crown Prince and the Prince of Liang entered the court together in the same carriage and did not dismount at the Sima Gate. Shizhi pursued and stopped them, forbidding them from entering the palace gate. He then impeached them for not dismounting at the public gate, an act of disrespect, and submitted the report. Empress Dowager Bo heard of it. Emperor Wen removed his cap and apologized, saying, "I have not taught my sons carefully." Empress Dowager Bo then sent an envoy with an imperial decree to pardon the Crown Prince and the Prince of Liang; only then were they allowed to enter. Emperor Wen thus regarded Shizhi as extraordinary and appointed him as Zhong Dafu.

Soon after, he became Zhonglangjiang. He accompanied the emperor to Bailing, where they stayed on the north side overlooking the latrine. At that time, Consort Shen was present. The emperor pointed to the road toward Xin Feng and said, "This is the road to Handan." He had Consort Shen play the se, while he himself leaned on the se and sang, his mood sorrowful and mournful. Turning to his ministers, he said, "Alas! If the coffin were made of northern mountain stone, stuffed with chopped hemp fiber, and lacquered between, could it be moved?" Those around him all said, "Good." Shizhi stepped forward and said, "If there is something desirable within it, even if the Southern Mountain were encased in metal, there would still be a crack; if there is nothing desirable within it, even without a stone coffin, what sorrow would there be?" Emperor Wen praised him. Later, he appointed Shizhi as Tingwei.

Soon after, the emperor went out through Zhongwei Bridge. A man rushed out from under the bridge, startling the imperial horses. The emperor ordered the cavalry to arrest him and handed him over to the Tingwei. Shizhi interrogated him. The man said, "I am a countryman. Hearing the ban on traffic, I hid under the bridge. After a long time, I thought the procession had passed, so I came out. Seeing the imperial carriage and horses, I ran." The Tingwei judged the case: one person violated the ban; the penalty should be a fine. Emperor Wen angrily said, "This man personally startled my horse. My horse was gentle; had it been another horse, would it not have thrown and injured me? Yet the Tingwei judges him only to a fine!" Shizhi said, "The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the whole world. If the law is thus and you make it heavier, the law will not be trusted by the people. Moreover, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered immediate execution, that would have been the end. Now that the case has been referred to the Tingwei, the Tingwei is the balance of the world. Once it tilts, all usage of law in the world will become uneven; where can the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this." After a long time, the emperor said, "The Tingwei's judgment is correct."

Later, someone stole a jade ring from before the seat of the High Temple. He was captured. Emperor Wen was enraged and handed him over to the Tingwei for trial. Shizhi examined the statutes regarding theft of ritual vessels and imperial articles used in ancestral temples and submitted a report, judging the penalty to be execution in the marketplace. Emperor Wen flew into a great rage, saying, "How lawless this man is, to steal vessels from the temple of the Former Emperor! I entrusted him to the Tingwei intending to exterminate his clan, yet you submit a judgment according to the law. This is not my intention in reverently serving the ancestral temple." Shizhi removed his cap, bowed his head to the ground, and apologized, saying, "The law is sufficient as it stands. Moreover, although the crimes are equal, they differ according to the degree of rebellion and compliance. Now, if one who steals from the ancestral temple is to have his clan exterminated, suppose, by the remotest chance, a foolish man were to take a handful of earth from Changling, how would Your Majesty increase the punishment?" After a long time, Emperor Wen discussed it with Empress Dowager Bo and then permitted the Tingwei's judgment. At that time, the Zhongwei, Marquis of Tiao, Zhou Yafu, and the Prime Minister of Liang, Marquis of Shandu, Wang Tiankai, seeing that Shizhi held impartial opinions, formed a close friendship with him. From then on, Tingwei Zhang was praised throughout the world.

Later, Emperor Wen died, and Emperor Jing ascended. Shizhi, fearing, claimed illness. He wished to resign and leave, but feared severe punishment; he wished to appear and apologize, but did not know how it would turn out. Following the plan of Wang Sheng, he finally appeared and apologized; Emperor Jing did not blame him.

Wang Sheng was skilled in the teachings of Huang-Lao and was a recluse. Once, when summoned to stand in the court, all Three Excellencies and Nine Ministers were assembled standing. Wang Sheng, an old man, said, "My sock is untied," and turning to Tingwei Zhang, he said, "Tie my sock for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone said to Wang Sheng, "Why did you alone humiliate Tingwei Zhang in public, making him kneel to tie your sock?" Wang Sheng said, "I am old and lowly; I know I can never be of real benefit to Tingwei Zhang. Tingwei Zhang is now a famous minister throughout the world. I therefore merely humiliated Tingwei, making him kneel to tie my sock, wishing thereby to honor him." The ministers heard of this, esteemed Wang Sheng, and respected Tingwei Zhang even more.

Tingwei Zhang served Emperor Jing for more than a year and became Prime Minister of the Prince of Huainan, still bearing the mark of his former fault. After a long time, Shizhi died. His son was named Zhang Zhi, courtesy name Changgong. He attained the rank of Dafu but was dismissed. Because he could not accommodate himself to the times, he remained unappointed for life.

Feng Tang's grandfather was from Zhao. His father moved to Dai. When Han rose, they moved to Anling. Tang was famous for filial piety and served as Chief of the Zhonglang Bureau under Emperor Wen. One day, Emperor Wen passed by in his carriage and asked Tang, "Old sir, how did you become a Lang? Where is your home?" Tang answered fully and truthfully. Emperor Wen said, "When I resided in Dai, my Supervisor of Food, Gao Qu, often spoke to me of the excellence of the Zhao general Li Qi, who fought below Julu. Now, whenever I eat, my thoughts are never absent from Julu. Do you know this?" Tang replied, "He is still not as good as the generals Lian Po and Li Mu." The emperor said, "Why?" Tang said, "My grandfather, when in Zhao, served as an Officer-General and was friendly with Li Mu. My father formerly served as Prime Minister of Dai and was friendly with the Zhao general Li Qi; he knew his character." Having heard about the characters of Lian Po and Li Mu, the emperor was greatly pleased and, striking his thigh, said, "Alas! If only I could have Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals now, how could I worry about the Xiongnu!" Tang said, "Your servant! Even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not use them." The emperor, angered, rose and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang and reproached him, saying, "Why did you publicly humiliate me? Was there no private place?" Tang apologized, saying, "A rustic like me does not know taboos."

At that time, the Xiongnu had just made a great invasion into Chaona, killing the Beidi Commandant Ang. The emperor, concerned about the Xiongnu incursions, finally asked Tang again, "How do you know I could not use Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied, "I have heard that in ancient times, when kings dispatched generals, they knelt and pushed the chariot wheel, saying, 'Within the threshold, I control it; beyond the threshold, the general controls it.' Military merit, ranks, and rewards were all decided outside and reported upon return. This is not empty talk. My grandfather said that when Li Mu served as a Zhao general stationed on the border, the rents from the military markets were all used by him to feast the soldiers; rewards and gifts were decided outside, without interference from the center. He was entrusted and held responsible for success, so Li Mu was able to exhaust his wisdom and ability. He dispatched 1,300 selected chariots, 13,000 mounted archers, and 100,000 soldiers worth a hundred gold each. Thus he drove the Chanyu northward, defeated the Donghu, destroyed the Danlin, restrained the powerful Qin to the west, and supported Han and Wei to the south. At that time, Zhao was nearly hegemonic. Later, King Qian of Zhao ascended; his mother was a courtesan. When King Qian ascended, he used the slander of Guo Kai and finally executed Li Mu, ordering Yan Ju to replace him. Thus the army was defeated and the soldiers fled, and they were captured and destroyed by Qin. Now I have secretly heard that Wei Shang, as Governor of Yunzhong, used all the rents from the military markets to feast his soldiers, and from his private funds, every five days he slaughtered an ox to feast guests, military officers, and attendants. Therefore the Xiongnu kept their distance and did not approach the passes of Yunzhong. Once the enemy entered, Shang led chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many of them. The soldiers were all sons of families, rising from the fields to join the army; how could they know the regulations of the foot and the five-man units? They fought with all their strength day after day, beheading enemies and capturing prisoners, and reported merit at the general's headquarters. If a single word did not correspond, the clerks would bind them by law. Their rewards were not carried out, while the officials strictly enforced the law. I, in my foolishness, believe that Your Majesty's law is too clear, rewards too light, and punishments too heavy. Moreover, the Governor of Yunzhong, Wei Shang, was convicted because his report of heads and captives differed by six. Your Majesty handed him over to the officials, stripped his rank, and sentenced him to penal labor. From this it follows that even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not use them. I am truly foolish; I have touched upon taboos. Death! Death!" Emperor Wen was pleased. On that day he ordered Feng Tang to hold the tally and pardon Wei Shang, restoring him as Governor of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as Commander of Chariots and Cavalry, in charge of the Zhongwei and the chariot troops of the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jing ascended and appointed Tang as Prime Minister of Chu, but he was dismissed. When Emperor Wu ascended, he sought the worthy and virtuous and recommended Feng Tang. Tang was then over ninety years old and could no longer serve as an official, so his son Feng Sui was made a Lang. Sui's courtesy name was Wangsun; he was also an extraordinary man and was friendly with me.

The Grand Historian says: Zhang Ji's words about worthy elders show that he upheld the law without bending to personal will; Lord Feng's discussion of generals is flavorful! Flavorful! As the saying goes, "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." The praises of these two gentlemen can be inscribed in the temple halls. The Book says, "Without bias and without faction, the royal way is broad; without faction and without bias, the royal way is smooth." Zhang Ji and Lord Feng are near to this. [end of text]


